FeedEntry.create(:id => 501, :name => "3 Challenges Implementing Lean UX in the Enterprise", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\nTransitioning teams to be more &#8220;lean&#8221; in their product development is not easy. This is especially true in larger, more established organizations. Years of historical momentum coupled with siloed bureaucracy and overzealous legal departments have entrenched a serial, lengthy process &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/3-challenges-implementing-lean-ux-in-the-enterprise/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/3-challenges-implementing-lean-ux-in-the-enterprise/", :published_at => Thu, 03 Jan 2013 15:38:28 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=426", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 502, :name => "Off on the right foot…", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\nIt&#8217;s January 2013 &#8211; the month and year I turn 40. I&#8217;m not one to get hung up on age. In fact I&#8217;m a big believer in that old saying that you&#8217;re only as old as you feel. I feel &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/off-on-the-right-foot/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/off-on-the-right-foot/", :published_at => Wed, 02 Jan 2013 14:31:03 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=424", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 503, :name => "Announcing Lean Day: UX – A Lean UX conference in New York City", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\nI&#8217;m very proud to announce the launch of Lean Day: UX &#8211; a one day, single track Lean UX conference taking place on March 1st, 2013 in New York City. Continuing on the success of this year&#8217;s Agile UX NYC, &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/announcing-lean-day-ux-a-lean-ux-conference-in-new-york-city/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/announcing-lean-day-ux-a-lean-ux-conference-in-new-york-city/", :published_at => Sat, 15 Dec 2012 15:24:33 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=419", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 504, :name => "We’ve joined New Context!", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\nI&#8217;m thrilled to share that Proof, the product design studio we (Giff Constable, Josh Seiden) founded earlier this year has been acquired by New Context. Starting immediately, we will be the NYC office of New Context offering a full array &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/weve-joined-new-context/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/weve-joined-new-context/", :published_at => Thu, 20 Sep 2012 21:12:12 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=416", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 505, :name => "Take that meeting…", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\n&#8220;I don&#8217;t really use LinkedIn or Twitter.&#8221; &#8220;I don&#8217;t go to meetups.&#8221; &#8220;I don&#8217;t really have time to meet people.&#8221; These are just a few of the phrases I hear all the time from people I come across &#8212; whether &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/take-that-meeting/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/take-that-meeting/", :published_at => Mon, 17 Sep 2012 15:48:24 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=413", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 506, :name => "Why have you not written anything here in 2 months?", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\nQuick update on the next blog post(s) coming up here. I&#8217;ve been swamped with launching a new business, speaking around the world, writing for a few other publications and putting the finishing touches on the Lean UX book. This has &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/why-have-you-not-written-anything-here-in-2-months/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/why-have-you-not-written-anything-here-in-2-months/", :published_at => Sat, 26 May 2012 20:00:09 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=399", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 507, :name => "Interaction design is not respected as a design discipline", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\nBack in February I was lucky enough to attend Interaction 12, the IxDA’s annual conference, in Dublin, Ireland. It was an incredibly well-produced event with lots of thoughtful sessions, interesting people and fun activities. One of those activities was the &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/interaction-design-is-not-respected-as-a-design-discipline/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/interaction-design-is-not-respected-as-a-design-discipline/", :published_at => Tue, 06 Mar 2012 20:06:24 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=386", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 508, :name => "Remote collaborative brainstorming and sketching – Part I", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\nI’ve been facilitating design studios with collocated teams for years. Many, including me, have covered the benefits of collaboratively sketching new ideas and concepts with a cross-functional team. Recently though, I was tasked with bringing this exercise to a distributed &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/remote-collaborative-brainstorming-and-sketching-part-i/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/remote-collaborative-brainstorming-and-sketching-part-i/", :published_at => Fri, 27 Jan 2012 14:43:41 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=340", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 509, :name => "I’m leaving TheLadders….and launching Proof!", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\n“Go to the edge of the cliff and jump off. Build your wings on the way down.” &#8211; Fahrenheit 451 author Ray Bradbury &#160; &#160; It’s a new year. And even though it’s mostly an arbitrary point in time, there’s &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/im-leaving-theladders-and-launching-proof/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/im-leaving-theladders-and-launching-proof/", :published_at => Wed, 11 Jan 2012 16:02:06 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=334", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 510, :name => "Using personas for executive alignment", :summary => "<style type=\"text/css\">\n#leftcontainerBox {\nfloat:left;\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 60%;\nleft: 70px;\n}\n\n#leftcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nclear:both;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n\npadding-bottom:2px;\n}\n\n\n#bottomcontainerBox {\nheight: 30px;\nwidth:50%;\npadding-top:1px;\n}\n\n#bottomcontainerBox .buttons {\nfloat:left;\nheight: 30px;\nmargin:4px 4px 4px 4px;\n}\n\n</style>\nA few weeks ago my colleague Michelle Zassenhaus suggested we pitch the executive team on a persona research project. We discussed the need and merit of this project for a while without reaching a clear consensus. Where I was getting &#8230; <a href=\"http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/using-personas-for-executive-alignment/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/using-personas-for-executive-alignment/", :published_at => Wed, 16 Nov 2011 18:54:13 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/?p=303", :feed_title => "Jeff Gothelf", :feed_id => 16)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 511, :name => "Co-founding as a Couple", :summary => "Founding a startup is hard work. The long hours and the constant worries take a heavy toll on all founders and even early employees. Founding a startup with your spouse or Significant Other can be even more challenging. My wife and I have been married for 12 years, and we&#8217;ve been together for 16. We resisted working&#8230; <a href=\"http://blog.luxr.co/co-founding-as-a-couple/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://blog.luxr.co/co-founding-as-a-couple/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=co-founding-as-a-couple", :published_at => Mon, 04 Mar 2013 23:31:31 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://blog.luxr.co/?p=2443", :feed_title => "LUXr", :feed_id => 17)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 512, :name => "The Lean Entrepreneur is here!", :summary => "Today&#8217;s mail brought amazing goodness to LUXr! We received our first 6 copies of The Lean Entrepreneur, the long-awaited book from our friends Brant Cooper and Patrick Vlaskovits. For years we&#8217;ve recommended their previous book, The Entrepreneur&#8217;s Guide to Customer Development, and followed them as they&#8217;ve charted new ground for entrepreneurship-done-right. So run and buy&#8230; <a href=\"http://blog.luxr.co/the-lean-entrepreneur-is-here/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a>", :url => "http://blog.luxr.co/the-lean-entrepreneur-is-here/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=the-lean-entrepreneur-is-here", :published_at => Thu, 28 Feb 2013 01:13:06 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://blog.luxr.co/?p=2420", :feed_title => "LUXr", :feed_id => 17)
