FeedEntry.create(:id => 544, :name => "I couldn't agree more with this", :summary => "<p><span><a href=\"http://twitter.com/bsesser\">@BSesser</a> wrote an amazing guide to taking advantage of your time as an NYU or MBA Student. My favorite part in particular is this word of advice:</span></p>\n<p><span><a href=\"http://landofdablind.tumblr.com/post/18253528436/aspiringentrepreneursatstern\"><a href=\"http://landofdablind.tumblr.com/post/18253528436/aspiringentrepreneursatstern\">http://landofdablind.tumblr.com/post/18253528436/aspiringentrepreneursatstern</a></a></span></p>\n<p><span><br/></span></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span>Look at the recently funded companies from investors like </span><a href=\"http://www.lererventures.com/\">Lerer Ventures</a><span>, </span><a href=\"http://svangel.com/\">SV Angel</a><span>, </span><a href=\"http://www.iaventures.com/\">IA Ventures</a><span>, </span><a href=\"http://www.rre.com/\">RRE</a><span>, </span><a href=\"http://foundercollective.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Founder Collective</a><span>, </span><a href=\"http://www.thrivecap.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Thrive Capital</a><span>, etc. across the first semester. </span><span> </span><span>Figure out the one with the most potential (in your opinion, not according to TechCrunch).</span><span>  </span><span>Think of 3-4 ways you can add immediate value to their business and aggressively pursue an unpaid internship for the semester. </span><span> </span><span>(When I was a first year this company was </span><a href=\"http://groupme.com/\">GroupMe</a><span>, and </span><a href=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/person/david-lee\">David Lee</a><span> told me so.</span><span>  </span><span>Whoops, should have done this…)</span></p>\n</blockquote>", :url => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/31799953778", :published_at => Tue, 18 Sep 2012 16:20:00 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/31799953778", :feed_title => "Trevor Owens", :feed_id => 19)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 545, :name => "7 Simple Rules for Reducing Email Within Your Team", :summary => "<p><div><ol><li>Only email someone when you need them to take a specific action</li>\n<li>Use Yammer for Questions</li>\n<li>Only CC/include those who need to be in the know (99% of the time this is not done)</li>\n<li>BCC people after they are not needed</li>\n<li>Try to gchat someone instead, as it won&#8217;t clog his/her inbox</li>\n<li>Don&#8217;t respond for the sake of responding</li>\n<li>Be respectful of people&#8217;s inboxes on the team, <strong>they usually need to be doing work not email :)</strong></li>\n</ol></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>BONUS: If you MUST send an email, keep it super-short and to the point</div></p>", :url => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/27891400546", :published_at => Tue, 24 Jul 2012 05:23:00 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/27891400546", :feed_title => "Trevor Owens", :feed_id => 19)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 546, :name => "Matt Mireles: The Importance of Running Lean", :summary => "<a href=\"http://mattmireles.com/post/24937484956/the-importance-of-running-lean\">Matt Mireles: The Importance of Running Lean</a>: <p><a class=\"tumblr_blog\" href=\"http://mattmireles.com/post/24937484956/the-importance-of-running-lean\">mattmireles</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>Failure is hard. Self delusion is worse.</strong></p>\n<p>Shortly after I started SpeakerText in the late 2000’s, The Lean Startup came into vogue as a meme. My understanding of the concept was pretty superficial:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Save money and be “lean” by launching shitty, ugly, barely-working products. If and when the…</p>\n</blockquote>\n</blockquote>", :url => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/25536436921", :published_at => Wed, 20 Jun 2012 23:27:20 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/25536436921", :feed_title => "Trevor Owens", :feed_id => 19)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 547, :name => "How to Spot a One Trick Pony", :summary => "<p>How do you separate luck from success? How do you know if someone&#8217;s a one trick pony?</p>\n<p>Whether someone is an early success or not, you can look at people&#8217;s long-term habbits that are important in personal growth.</p>\n<ul><li>Insatiable Curiosity</li>\n<li>Workaholism</li>\n<li>Extreme Empathy</li>\n<li>Keeps Promises/Returns Favors</li>\n<li>Brings Others Up to His/Her Level</li>\n</ul><p>Short-term thinking &amp; behaviors are the telling sign of a one trick pony, beware at all costs.</p>", :url => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/24553552506", :published_at => Wed, 06 Jun 2012 19:31:00 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/24553552506", :feed_title => "Trevor Owens", :feed_id => 19)
FeedEntry.create(:id => 548, :name => "Your 15 Minutes Will Run Out", :summary => "<p>Once you&#8217;re lucky, twice your good. But you still don&#8217;t have the midas touch. Success should be a warning sign, while failure is the opportunity to buy low.</p>\n<p>Everyone&#8217;s hot will fizzle, and anyone can be the next big thing. But that&#8217;s just a cop out. Rational altruism is a game, and the game is for players. No one likes to be played.</p>", :url => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/24322202812", :published_at => Sun, 03 Jun 2012 09:59:32 UTC +00:00, :guid => "http://trevorowens.tumblr.com/post/24322202812", :feed_title => "Trevor Owens", :feed_id => 19)
